    <div class='steps'>
        <div class='step' id='step1'>
            <p>The city's recycling push has been years in the making, largely focusing on communities that had historically low diversion rates, which mostly translated to less affluent districts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step2'>
            <p>The push was fueled by the poverty-stricken districts that recycled considerably more, particularly in the Bronx.</p>
            <p class='note'>**High poverty rate defined as greater than 15%</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step2'>
            <p>The Department of Sanitation's concerted education efforts with neighborhood institutions in the last decade helped bridge cultural barriers, such as language, in these areas, according to Espinoza.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step3'>
            <p>But when it came to districts that are recycling less, the five culprits were spread across lower Manhattan, Staten Island and Brooklyn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step-'>
            <p>The two chart-topping districts are among the high-wealth cluster in lower Manhattan and northweste Brooklyn.</p>
            <p class='note'>**High income defined as a district having a median household income of greater than $90,000. The city's median is nearly $58,000, per the Census.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step4'>
            <p>These Manhattan districts, CD 1 and CD 6, faced the starkest drops.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step5'>
            <p>The greatest fall was in the elite Community District 1, which contains Wall Street, Tribeca and Battery Park City. The district's diversion rate fell six percentage points, from 53% in 2009 to 47% in 2018.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='step' id='step5'>
            <p>It's also tied for the wealthiest in the city with a median household income of $121,000, more than double the city's median of nearly $58,000.</p>
        </div>
        
